article.description:
Dana Cherry scored 23 points, and India
Lewis added 18 as No. 11 Arkansas won at Memphis for the first time
in seven tries by defeating the Tigers 78-64 Thursday night.
article.headline: Razorbacks shoot 58 percent in first half
article.linkText: Arkansas gets first victory in Memphis with rout
article.story:
MEMPHIS, Tenn. (AP) -- In his 10 seasons as Arkansas women's
basketball coach, Gary Blair has taken the Lady Razorbacks to a
Final Four, a Women's National Invitation Tournament title and
three appearances in Top 10 national rankings.

	   Before Thursday night's game, however, he hadn't had much
success in Memphis.

	   Winless in two previous trips, Blair overcame his Memphis blues
with a 78-64 victory. The win also represented the Lady Razorbacks'
first against the Lady Tigers in seven tries in Memphis.

	   "That was the main focus of the seniors," said Dana Cherry,
who led Arkansas  (No. 10 ESPN/USA Today, No. 11 AP) with 23 points. "We talked about having never won
here since we've been at Arkansas. We came out with a lot of
intensity. We were ready to play. We were ready to win."

	   While Cherry scored most of her points on aggressive drives,
fellow senior guard India Lewis proved productive from the
perimeter. She finished with 22 points, including four 3-point
baskets.

	   The Lady Razorbacks (13-2), who open Southeastern Conference
play Sunday at home against South Carolina, played as if they did
not want to give Memphis an opportunity for the upset.

	   Arkansas shot 58.1 percent in the first half to build a 20-point
lead.

	   Shameka Christon added 14 points and 10 rebounds in the 399th
victory of Arkansas coach Gary Blair's 18-year career. And the Lady
Razorbacks used an effective 2-3 zone, a defense they don't
normally employ, to shut down Memphis's leading scorer, Shannon
Hamp, in the first half.

	   Hamp finished with 15 points, but was held to four in the first
half as the Lady Razorbacks pulled away to a 47-27 lead.

	   "We know everybody is going to play zone because of our
inconsistency in our perimeter shooting," Memphis coach Joye
Lee-McNelis said. "In the first six minutes Hamp only touched the
ball one time -- one time. I kept yelling that we had to get the
ball in the hands of our leading scorer."

	   Lewis said the defense was a key factor in the win.

	   "We're not a zone team," she said. "But it was effective.
Every time Hamp touched the ball, we doubled down on her."

	   The Lady Tigers (6-6) also got 15 points from Raven Rogers while
losing for the sixth time in eight games.

	   Lewis and Cherry hit 16-of-28 attempts from the field to help
Arkansas shoot 50 percent.

	   Memphis struggled from the field against the taller, more
athletic Lady Razorbacks, shooting 36.7 percent in the second half
and 39.7 percent for the game.

	   The Lady Razorbacks pulled away midway through the first half
behind Lewis and Christon. A 3-pointer by Lewis gave Arkansas a
22-12 lead with 12 minutes to go, and a 10-0 run near the end of
the half, which included five points from Lewis, extended the lead.

	   In the second half, Memphis trimmed the lead to 63-50 after a
3-pointer by Rogers, but the Tigers were unable to get any closer,
in part because of their poor free-throw shooting. Memphis made
just 15-of-29 attempts.
